Zachary Karate Club is a famous example traditionally used by network scientist of a university karate club described in the paper An Information Flow Model for Conflict and Fission in Small Groups by Wayne W. Zachary. The network became THE EXAMPLE of community structure in networks after its use by Michelle Girvan and Mark Newman in 2002.

## Zachary's karate club
g <- make_graph("Zachary")




  sg <- cluster_spinglass(g)

  ## Double check the result
  print(modularity(sg))
## [1] 0.4197896
  print(modularity(g, membership(sg)))
## [1] 0.4197896
  ## Compare to the greedy optimizer
  fc <- cluster_fast_greedy(g)
  print(modularity(fc))
## [1] 0.3806706
plot(sg,g)

plot(fc,g)

membership(sg)
##  [1] 3 3 3 3 1 1 1 3 2 2 1 3 3 3 2 2 1 3 2 3 2 3 2 4 4 4 2 4 4 2 2 4 2 2
membership(fc)
##  [1] 1 3 3 3 1 1 1 3 2 3 1 1 3 3 2 2 1 3 2 1 2 3 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2 2

You can compare community structures using various metrics

compare(fc,sg,method = "vi")
## [1] 0.8634332
metodos<-c("vi", "nmi", "split.join", "rand",
  "adjusted.rand")
comparative<-c()
for (i in 1:length(metodos)){
comparative[i]<-compare(fc,sg,metodos[i])
}
comparative
## [1]  0.8634332  0.6340649 14.0000000  0.7789661  0.4873919
for (i in 1:length(metodos)){
comparative[i]<-compare(fc,fc,metodos[i])
}
comparative
## [1] 0 1 0 1 1
